The fix is to bypass `IFormFile` entirely and read the multipart stream manually. Here's the approach:

**1. Disable request size limits and buffering:**

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(o =>
{
    o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
});
```

**2. Stream to disk using `MultipartReader`:**

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt) ||
        string.IsNullOrEmpty(mt.Boundary.Value))
    {
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");
    }

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary).Value!;
    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);

    MultipartSection? section;
    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) ||
            !cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            continue;
        }

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize name
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var fs = new FileStream(savePath, FileMode.Create);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**3. On the endpoint, disable the buffering attribute:**

```csharp
.WithMetadata(new DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute());
```

**Why this works:** `MultipartReader` reads the stream in small chunks (default 16 KB buffer inside `CopyToAsync`), so memory stays flat regardless of file size.

**Key gotchas:**
- Never trust `cd.FileName` directly — sanitize or replace it.
- If behind IIS/Nginx, raise their limits too (`maxAllowedContentLength` / `client_max_body_size`).
- Add a `CancellationToken` parameter to support client disconnects gracefully.
